me in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jean II de Grandpré-Buzancy was born in 1240, in Grandpré, Ardennes, Grand Est, France, his father, Henry de Grandpré Fifth, was 25 and his mother, Isabeau de Brienne, was 28. He had at least 1 daughter with Jeanne de Grandpre. He died in 1314, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","–1347":"–1347","1275–1325":"1275–1325","1215–1287":"1215–1287","1212–1274":"1212–1274","1314":"1314","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1212":"1212","1287":"1287","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","Grandpré, Vouziers, Ardennes, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Grandpré, Ardennes, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Grandpré, Ardennes, Grand Est, France":"Grandpré, Ardennes, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","–1347":"–1347","1275–1325":"1275–1325","1215–1287":"1215–1287","1212–1274":"1212–1274","1314":"1314","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1212":"1212","1287":"1287","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","Grandpré, Vouziers, Ardennes, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Grandpré, Ardennes, Grand Est, Ranska","Grandpré, Ardennes, Grand Est, France":"Grandpré, Ardennes, Grand Est, Ranska"},"fr":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","–1347":"–1347","1275–1325":"1275–1325","1215–1287":